<https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/maximum-drawdown-mdd.asp> a invp:Term ;
    rdfs:label "Maximum Drawdown (MDD) Definition" ;
    schema:url <https://www.investopedia.com/terms/m/maximum-drawdown-mdd.asp> ;
    invp:description """
A maximum drawdown (MDD) is the maximum observed loss from a peak to a trough of a portfolio, before a new peak is attained. Maximum drawdown is an indicator of downside risk over a specified time period.

It can be used both as a stand-alone measure or as an input into other metrics such as "Return over Maximum Drawdown" and the <a data-component="link" data-ordinal="1" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/calmarratio.asp" rel="noopener noreferrer">Calmar Ratio</a>. Maximum Drawdown is expressed in percentage terms.

<span data-value="\\begin{aligned} MDD=\\frac{\\textit{Trough Value}-\\textit{Peak Value}}{\\textit{Peak Value}}\\end{aligned}">﻿<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">
